11/ So get vaccinated, get your booster when you are supposed to, mask up and take care of each other. As always, thanks for your encouragement and support and apologies for typos. Can't blame that on covid...#COVID19 #CovidIsNotOver

10/That means--despite the fact that I live in a place without a mask mandate or social distancing, I'm choosing to do it. There is a reason that Baltimore --and their awesome health department @BMore_Healthy--has lower infection rates than anyplace in the state.

9/Which gets to my final point. We seem to have decided that we are going to do some version of the Great Barrington Declaration to get through the pandemic--that means we are back to having to make personal decisions about our safety.
8/ But we quickly created one and I'm relieved to say my husband did not get covid (critical period is two days before symptoms and 5 days after)

7/ A couple of things I'd recommend to everyone: if/when you get covid, how will you quarantine? Ideally you can separate from your partner/kids, easier said than done. Separate bathrooms/bedrooms/ventilation/figuring out how to get food etc. We didn't have a plan.

6/Speaking of long covid, I'm still pretty congested and can't smell (but I think that's the congestion). The public health nurse said that could last for months and it is a long covid thing (mild, thankfully)

5/ Donna the public health nurse made a couple of things clear: my immunity system is weakened and I need to be careful about catching even a cold. Pneumonia and other long covid issues could still sneak up. She recommended naps and rest, even though I feel ok.

4/The media seems slow to catch up to the reality that I'm not alone, breakthrough cases are more prevalent that we know. Sadly, we won't really know everything we could because the CDC is not tracking them (there are some good cohort studies happening, but that's not the same).
3/I'm also grateful that the state of MD and a public health nurse (my new bestie Donna) were in touch and answered my questions
2/I was not hospitalized and my blood ox level was always good. Vaccines work, and they did their job with me. I'm grateful for that.
1/ My breakthrough infection was no joke. It wasn't mild, I spent most of the last week with fever around 101.5 and heavy congestion BUT
